flights.notes: First Block 5 Falcon 9 to be launched.
First reflight of a Block 5 Falcon 9.
First Falcon booster to fly from three different launch pads.
Mission demonstrated Dragon's ability to escape off of Falcon 9 in case of an emergency. The booster was destroyed by aerodynamic forces after the escape.
Booster was not recovered per the mission requirments.
Landed Successfully despite bad weather.
First landing at LZ-4.
One payload was sent to lunar orbit. Another small test satellite.
First operational Starlinks! First flight to refly fairings.
On accent an engine failure occurred due to cleaning fluid stuck inside a sensor in the engine. May have caused another engine failure during the decent.
Finial launch of Iridium satellites with SpaceX in the NEXT contract. All satellites were deployed successfully.
First large launch batch of Starlink satellites (60). They were of production design but not yet operational.
Only launched 58 satellites. Three customer satellites on top of Starlink stack.
First booster to fly for the 7th time.
Launched out of order (18,19 launched before). Unknown issue caused second stage deorbit failure, resulting in an uncontrolled deorbit over the United Sates. Some debris reached the ground.
Grid fin hydraulic pump stalled. Made a soft water landing.
First launch of a crew-rated version of Dragon.
Launched three satellites, prior to deployment they can be seen moving into position for deployment.
Only launched 57 Starlinks. 2 other customer satellites deployed from on top of Starlink stack.
First time a customer flew on a booster with significant flights. Also first dedicated customer launch where fairings were previously flown.
First booster to fly 10 missions.
First Block 5 variant of the Falcon Heavy to be launched.
First Block 5 variant of the Falcon Heavy to be launched.
Per the mission requirements the booster was expended.
After a good landing, center core fell over in the seas because octograbber was not configured for the center core .
Booster was loaded with incorrect data leading to a landing failure.
High entry forces and heat caused the TVC in the center engine to fail causing the landing to fail.
Mission successfully launched Bob Behnken and Doug Hurley safely to the ISS.
First cargo launch of new Dragon variant.
143 customer and Starlink satellites deployed, a record at that time. First Starlinks to go into polar orbit. First time a payload was deployed from aft end of stage 2.
Only 52 Starlinks deployed. One customer satellite deoplyed from top of Starlink stack, the other from aft end.
Last flight of original Cargo Dragon
Only launched 58 satellites. Three customer satellites deployed from top of Starlink stack.
First polar launch from from Florida since the 1960s. Also carried two other smallsats passengers.
First NROL launch on a booster with significant flight history.

Engine boot, a cover, developed a hole leading to hot gases to leak into engine. As a result the engine was shutdown inflight. Same engine was needed for recovery of booster. Hole developed on boot with highest flight experience of its kind.
Deployed 88 satellites, including 3 Starlinks, Some payloads deployed from aft of Falcon. Tyvak-0173 had a delayed separation confirmation,
Successfully launched Mike Hopkins, Victor Glover, Shannon Walker, and Sochi Noguchi.
Launched Shane Kimbrough, Megan McArthur, Akihiki "Aki" Hoshide, and Thomas Pesquet to the ISS. First crewed mission to use reused booster and capsule.
First landing on A Shortfall of Gravitas.
Initial launch was scrubbed due to higher then expected pressure in the gas generators due to left over lacquer.
First NSSL mission to fly on a reused booster.
Uncrewed orbital test flight of Dragon 2. Capsule was destroyed in subsequent testing due to major design flaws.
Dragon successfully escaped from Falcon 9.
Carried Bob Behnken and Doug Hurley safely to the ISS and back.
Carried Shane Kimbrough, Megan McArthur, Akihiki "Aki" Hoshide, and Thomas Pesquet to the ISS.
First operational flight. Successfully carried Mike Hopkins, Victor Glover, Shannon Walker, and Sochi Noguchi.
First Dragon 2 cargo mission,
First stage flight preceded nominally.  Second stage was terminated by range due to telemetry loss. Loss of telemetry was due to a ground side issue, and not Electron.
First successful flight.
Carried advanced instrumentation to measure the re-entry regimes.
First guided re-entry of booster using RCS to reoriented the vehicle engine first. Heat shield collapse was noted. First fully AFTS.
Second guided re-entry of booster. Both booster crashed into the ocean,
First stage preformed nominally. Intermittently secure wiring caused heating and potting compound around it to melt. Subsequently disconnecting the wire, causing engine turbopumps to shutdown.

electron.name: I Can't Believe Its not Optical

flights.missionName: I Can't Believe Its not Optical
flights.notes: First launch of Photon bus.
Guided re-entry followed by parachute deploy. Booster was successfully recovered from ocean.

Reused some components from "Return To Sender" mission. Nominal first stage assent and recovery. Second stage engine had a igniter issue causing single corruption making TVC to deviate. Engine computer reacted to deviation by commanding zero pump speed - leading to engine shutdown.

electron.name: It's A Little Chile Up Here

flights.missionName: It's A Little Chile Up Here

flights.notes: Capsule landed safely. Booster crashed.
First successful landing of New Shepard booster; first time vertical landing of vehicle reaching space.
First successful refight of a flown booster.
Third flight of same booster.
Capsule successfully aborted from booster.
Successful high altitude abort.
Carried Wally Funk, Oliver Daemen, Mark Bezos, and Jeff Bezos to space and back.
